If moderates don't show, McCaskill might be slightly more likely to take it.  But I suspect more moderates than usual will go to the polls and, if for no other reason, vote conservative out of habit, though there's much more evidence to show they'll vote party to keep Republicans in the majority.  If they aren't sure now that they're leaning toward McCaskill (and many seem not to be), I very much doubt that another month will do a lot to shift things.  And for registered likely voters, they lean conservative and may have mixed feelings about Hawley but are very clear in general about what they like and don't like about McCaskill.  She doesn't have much room to move and she'll only win if Hawley or Trump turn people off more than has already happened.  The best thing McCaskill has going for her is experience, and the the likely moderates seem, unfortunately for her, least likely to be impressed with her record.

Democratic incumbent Sen. Claire McCaskill leads Republican challenger Josh Hawley by 4 percentage points among likely voters when third party candidates are included, according to an NBC News/Marist poll released Tuesday.
McCaskill’s edge among likely voters falls within the poll’s margin of error, signaling a tight contest in one of this year’s most important Senate races.
President Trump’s aggressive trade policy hasn’t resonated with Missouri voters, according to the poll. Only 28 percent of likely voters believe tariffs protect jobs and help the economy.

While there is no new news or polls, a couple of factors influence my slight downgrade (of 1%):
- Trump job approval has not tanked significantly, despite the fierce attack on the illegal immigrants' children issue. It does decrease, but his job disapproval rating surprisingly has decreased to 52%. 
- In April poll, Trump has job approval of 55% in MO, so it may be risky for McCaskill to play anti-Trump card
- Her main challenger Hawley  is relatively unknown, but scandal around the R-Governor may boost his  name recognition. The scandal didn't tank Hawley despite great effort by McCaskill to tie Hawley with the disgraced governor. Early August Primary may boost even more Hawley's name recognition. 
- Once Hawley clears the Primary hurdle, more money will pour into his campaign since McCaskill is considered the most vulnerable among tossup races. If McCaskill remains in the Senate, the Democrats would likely flip the Senate by more than 4 seats. But if Blue Wave fizzles, McCaskill would be the first peg to fall.

The election will fill the Class 1 Senate seat held by Claire McCaskill (D). She was first elected in 2006. With McCaskill the last Democrat in Missouri to win a statewide election in 2012, Republicans are closely watching this race because of its potential to change party hands.[4] Contenders in the Republican field include state legislator Paul Curtman and Missouri Attorney General Josh Hawley. Politico also reported in August 2017 that Club for Growth had raised $10 million to support Hawley's run, before he had declared his candidacy.[5] While McCaskill did not face a primary challenger in 2012 when she was elected to a second term in office, she could face increased pressure from more progressive members of her party in 2018. Her first challenger, Angelica Earl, for example, has called for a single-payer healthcare system—a policy which McCaskill said that she could not yet support.[6][7] McCaskill has significant party support, however, and set a record in the first quarter of 2017 for the most money raised by a Senate candidate in Missouri during a nonelection year.[8] In the fourth quarter of 2017, McCaskill raised $2.9 million; Hawley raised $959,000 over the same time period.[9] This seat was rated, on average, a Toss-up by three outlets as of January 23, 2018.[10] CNN listed this seat among 10 U.S. Senate seats it considered most likely to flip in 2018
